      "role": "assistant",
      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"workouts\":[{\"day_of_week\":1,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Aerobic Run\",\"target_distance_km\":10,\"target_duration_minutes\":62,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":372,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":372,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":385,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Start very relaxed, just settling into your stride. No pressure here.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":52,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":372,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Hold a comfortable, conversational pace throughout. This is aerobic base work — your breathing should feel easy enough to hold a full sentence.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":385,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Ease off gradually. Let your heart rate drift down naturally.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Begin at the very easy end of your easy pace range (around 6:11/km) for the first 5 minutes before settling into your comfortable aerobic rhythm.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Last 5 minutes, let the pace drift back toward 6:11/km. Follow up with light dynamic stretching, especially for calves and Achilles.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Monday's easy run is all about aerobic stimulus without accumulated fatigue. Given your training history — you've been averaging 62–64 km on full weeks — this 10 km sits comfortably within your maintenance range. Easy days are where a huge proportion of your aerobic adaptations happen, and they're also what allow you to hit quality sessions later in the week with real energy. Keep this genuinely easy: if in doubt, slow down.\",\"perceived_effort\":4},{\"day_of_week\":2,\"workout_type\":\"Tempo\",\"title\":\"Threshold Cruise Intervals\",\"target_distance_km\":13,\"target_duration_minutes\":70,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":372,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":269,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":15,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":372,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"15 minutes easy, fully relaxed. The warmup is doing real work here — don't shortchange it.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":10,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":269,\"intensity\":\"Threshold\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"First threshold cruise interval at 4:29/km. This should feel comfortably hard — controlled, not labored. You can speak a short phrase but not hold a conversation.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Recovery\",\"duration_minutes\":2,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":372,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy jog recovery. Use this to reset your breathing before the next effort.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":10,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":269,\"intensity\":\"Threshold\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Second threshold interval. Maintain the same controlled effort — avoid the temptation to push harder than the first one.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Recovery\",\"duration_minutes\":2,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":372,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy jog recovery again.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":10,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":269,\"intensity\":\"Threshold\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Third and final cruise interval. If you're feeling strong, this one should feel like the smoothest of the three — your body is warmed up and tuned in.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":15,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":385,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"15 minutes easy to flush lactate and bring your system down gradually. Don't skip this — it matters for tomorrow.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Full 15-minute easy warmup at 6:00–6:11/km before touching threshold pace. Include 4–6 light strides in the final 2 minutes if you're feeling tight.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"15 minutes easy at 6:00–6:11/km. Followed by calf raises and gentle Achilles mobility given your tendinitis history.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Threshold cruise intervals are one of the highest-value workouts in your maintenance toolkit. Three 10-minute efforts at 4:29/km with short 2-minute recoveries raises your lactate threshold — the pace you can sustain for prolonged efforts — without the deep fatigue of a full tempo run. For a runner of your caliber maintaining fitness, this is the kind of session that keeps your aerobic ceiling high. The 2-minute jog recoveries are intentionally short: this is a threshold session, not an interval session. Resist going faster; the magic is in the sustained effort, not the speed.\",\"perceived_effort\":7},{\"day_of_week\":3,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Recovery-Paced Easy Run\",\"target_distance_km\":8,\"target_duration_minutes\":52,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":385,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":385,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":52,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":385,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Stay at the slow end of your easy range today — 6:11/km or even a touch slower if your legs are asking for it. This is a recovery run in disguise: it keeps your aerobic engine ticking without adding meaningful stress.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"No formal warmup needed — the whole run IS your warmup. Start easy and stay easy.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Finish with 5 minutes of walking and light stretching. Pay attention to left calf and Achilles tightness — if anything feels off, note it.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"The day after a threshold session, your body is doing quiet but important repair work. An 8 km run at 6:11/km keeps blood flowing and reinforces aerobic habit without interfering with that recovery. This is one of the most underappreciated sessions in any training week — it's not glamorous, but it's the glue. Think of Wednesday's effort as investing in Friday's quality session.\",\"perceived_effort\":3},{\"day_of_week\":4,\"workout_type\":\"Interval\",\"title\":\"VO2max Track Intervals\",\"target_distance_km\":13,\"target_duration_minutes\":68,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":372,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":248,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":15,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":372,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Full 15-minute easy warmup. Include 4–6 acceleration strides in the last 3 minutes — build smoothly to interval pace and back down over about 20 seconds each. This primes your neuromuscular system.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":248,\"intensity\":\"VO2Max\",\"repetitions\":5,\"notes\":\"5 x 5 minutes at 4:08/km with 3-minute easy jog recoveries between each. This is hard but controlled — not a sprint. You should feel like you're working at the edge of what you can sustain for 5 minutes. Each rep should feel similar in effort; if the last ones feel dramatically harder, you may have gone out slightly too fast.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Recovery\",\"duration_minutes\":3,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":372,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":5,\"notes\":\"3-minute easy jog between each interval. Don't stop — keep moving. This active recovery clears metabolic byproducts and primes you for the next rep.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":15,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":385,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"15-minute easy cooldown. This is non-negotiable after a VO2max session — your heart rate and lactate need time to come down safely and efficiently.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"15 minutes easy with 4–6 strides at the end. On a track, this is a great chance to settle into the space and mentally prepare for the work ahead.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"15 minutes easy cooldown, ideally on flat ground. Gentle calf stretches and foam rolling afterward, especially left Achilles.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"VO2max intervals are the cornerstone of maintaining your aerobic ceiling. Five 5-minute efforts at 4:08/km with 3-minute recovery jogs delivers a powerful stimulus to your maximal oxygen uptake — the physiological engine that underpins your marathon performance. For a maintenance phase, the goal here isn't to push deeper into new territory; it's to preserve the fitness gains you've built. The 3-minute recoveries are slightly longer than threshold recoveries because the intensity is meaningfully higher — that recovery time is necessary for each interval to be high quality. A track or flat measured route works best so you can hit the pace consistently.\",\"perceived_effort\":8},{\"day_of_week\":5,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Aerobic Run with Strides\",\"target_distance_km\":10,\"target_duration_minutes\":60,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":372,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":231,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":385,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Ease into the run gently — your legs have done real work this week already.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":40,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":372,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Comfortable easy pace throughout. Conversational effort, relaxed form.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":10,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":231,\"intensity\":\"Repetition\",\"repetitions\":6,\"notes\":\"6 x 20-second strides at your repetition pace (around 3:51/km), with 60-second easy jog between each. Strides are not sprints — think smooth, tall, and quick. They wake up your fast-twitch muscle fibers and keep your neuromuscular system sharp without meaningful fatigue.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":385,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Easy 5-minute wind-down before tomorrow's long run.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Start gently and let the legs loosen naturally. No pressure to hit pace early.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Keep the cooldown easy and unhurried. A short walking cool-down after the run can help transition into rest before Sunday's long run. Light Achilles mobility work recommended.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Saturday's easy run with strides serves two purposes: it maintains your easy aerobic volume while the strides recruit fast-twitch fibers and keep your leg turnover sharp — something that can quietly erode during maintenance phases if you're only running easy. Six 20-second strides are well within what your body can handle before a long run; they're short enough to be non-taxing but meaningful enough to keep your neuromuscular efficiency dialed in. Think of strides as a tune-up, not a workout.\",\"perceived_effort\":4},{\"day_of_week\":0,\"workout_type\":\"LongRun\",\"title\":\"Long Aerobic Run\",\"target_distance_km\":20,\"target_duration_minutes\":118,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":372,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":372,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":8,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":385,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Start at the slow end of your easy range — 6:11/km or slower — for the first 8 minutes. Let your body settle in before asking anything of it.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":90,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":372,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Settle into a comfortable, easy aerobic rhythm between 5:24 and 6:11/km based on feel and terrain. The goal is time on feet at a sustainable effort — not pace. If it's a hilly route, let your effort guide you over the pace number.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":10,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":385,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Ease off in the final 10 minutes. Let the pace drift back to 6:11/km or slower. This final wind-down is part of the long run's purpose — landing gently matters.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Begin at 6:11/km or slightly slower for the first 8–10 minutes. Resist the urge to \\\"find your rhythm\\\" too quickly — let it come to you.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk 5–10 minutes after finishing. Rehydrate immediately and have a carbohydrate and protein source within 30–45 minutes. Gentle calf and hip flexor stretching. Pay specific attention to left Achilles post-run.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Your long run sits at 20 km this week, consistent with your recent training history (you've been running 18–21 km long runs over the past month). In a maintenance phase, the long run's primary job is to preserve your aerobic endurance base and muscular resilience — not to push new distance boundaries. Keeping it at 20 km within your 120-minute cap is the right call. Pace should be genuinely easy: 5:24–6:11/km, with effort as your primary guide on hills or warm days. Easy long runs build mitochondrial density, fat oxidation efficiency, and connective tissue resilience — all things that matter enormously for an advanced marathoner staying sharp between training blocks. Fuel every 45–60 minutes if you're out for more than 75 minutes.\",\"perceived_effort\":5}]}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
